<H3> <TI>   Discrete-Variational Hartree-Fock-Slater Calculations of </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discrete-Variational Hartree-Fock-Slater Calculations of </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Boron   2p Electron Density of States of Various Boron 
Compounds and Their Comparison With K-V X-Ray Emission Spectra 

<F P=102> 43070061I Tokyo ISBB'93 in English Aug 93 p 48--FOR OFFICIAL 
USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 43070061I </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ISBB'93 </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [English abstract of article by Jun Kawai, Masayoshi </F>
Kobayashi, and lwami Higashi, Institute of Physical and Chemical 
Research (RIKEN); Yasuji Muramatsu, NTT Interdisciplinary 
Research Laboratories; and Hirohiko Adachi, Department of 
Metallurgy, Kyoto University] 
  [Text] The K-V (K_a_) X-ray emission 
(fluorescence) spectra are emitted by the electric dipole 
transition of an electron from 2p to 1s 
orbital after the photoionization of one of the 1s 
electron (V denotes valence hole state). The 
2p orbitals of boron, carbon, nitrogen, and fluorine 
form valence molecular orbitals (i.e., a valence band) in the 
compounds. Therefore the K-V X-ray line shapes 
represent the local (X-ray emitting atom) and partial 
(2p) electron density of states (DOS) of the 
compounds. The discrete-variational (DV) Hartree-Fock-Slater 
(X_a_) calculations of carbon 2p DOS of 
various carbon compounds have successfully reproduced the 
measured carbon K-V X-ray line shapes of benzene, 
C[.sub]60[/],[.sup]1[/] C[.sub]70[/],[.sup]2[/] 
graphite, and diamond.[.sup]3[/] We then extend these 
calculations to various boron compounds in the present paper. 
The boron 2p DOS of various boron compounds (B, 
B[.sub]4[/]C, BN, B[.sub]2[/]O[.sub]3[/], 
B[.sub]6[/]O, BF[.sub]3[/], ...) are calculated by the 
DV-X_a_ method with a cluster-molecule approximation, 
where, e.g., B[.sub]12[/] molecule is calculated in place of 
a solid boron. The calculated B 2p DOS is compared 
with the measured X-ray emission spectra in the literature, 
resulting in satisfactory agreement between the calculation and 
the experiment. 
References 
  1. J. Kawai, K. Maeda, M. Takami, Y. Muramatsu, T. Hayashi, 
M. Motoyama, and Y. Saito, J. CHEM. PHYS., 1 March 1993 (in 
press). 
  2. J. Kawai and M. Motoyama, PHYS. REV., B (submitted). 
  3. J. Kawai, et al., (to be published). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

