<F P=100> Advanced Materials </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resonant Reemission of BK_a_ Emission Spectra of </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resonant Reemission of BK_a_ Emission Spectra of </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Boron   Oxide and Boron Nitride 

<F P=102> 43070061J Tokyo ISBB'93 in English Aug 93 p 49--FOR OFFICIAL 
USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 43070061J </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ISBB'93 </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [English abstract of article by Yasuji Muramatsu, Tom </F>
Scimeca, and Masaharu Oshima, NTT Interdisciplinary Research 
Laboratories; Jun Kawai, Institute of Physical and Chemical 
Research (RIKEN); and Hiroo Kato, Photon Factory, National 
Laboratory for High Energy Physics] 
  [Text] Recently, several X-ray emission threshold 
experiments have been attempted to elucidate satellite 
structures in X-ray emission spectra using monochromatized 
synchrotron radiation.[.sup]1,2[/] The satellite structure in 
BK_a_ emission spectra of boron oxide and boron nitride is 
particularly interesting because the origin of the high- energy 
satellites is not predicted from DV-X_a_ molecular orbital 
calculations.[.sup]3[/] The aim of this study is to 
investigate the satellite structure in the BK_a_ emission 
spectra of the boron compounds from threshold experiments using 
highly brilliant undulator radiation as an excitation probe. 
  Spectroscopic measurements were carried out on a fluorescent 
X-ray spectrometer of sophisticated design[.sup]4,5[/] 
installed on an undulator beamline (BL-16U)[.sup]6,7[/] at 
the Photon Factory. 
  A prominent increase in the high-energy satellite peak 
heights was first observed when the excitation energy was tuned 
to the narrow pre-edge peak in the B1s absorption spectrum 
corresponding to the transition from B(1s) to an unoccupied 
anti-bonding orbital (pã*). It is therefore confirmed that 
the 
high-energy satellites originate from resonant reemission due to 
a B(1s)-pã* -B(1s[.sup]-l[/]) transition. This resonant 
reemission phenomenon reflects the electric structure of the 
localized anti-bonding pã* orbital in 
trigonal-planar-structured boron compounds. 
References 
  1. R.D. Deslattes, R.E. LaVilla, P.L. Cowan, and A. Henins, 
PHYS. REV. A, Vol 27 No 2, 1983, p 923. 
  2. P.L. Cowan, PHYSICA SCRIPTA, Vol T31, 1990, p 112. 
  3. C. Satoko, M. Tsukada, and H. Adachi, J. PHYS. SOC. JPN., 
Vol 45, 1978, p 1333. 
  4. Y. Muramatsu, M. Oshima, T. Shoji, and H. Kato, REV. SCI. 
INSTR., Vol 63 No 12, 1992, p 5597. 
  5. Y. Muramatsu, M. Oshima, J. Kawai, and H. Kato, NUCL. 
INSTR. AND METHODS, (in press). 
  6. Y. Muramatsu and H. Maezawa, REV. SCI. INSTR., Vol 60 No 
7, 1989, p2078. 
  7. Y. Muramatsu, H. Kato, H. Maezawa, and T. Harada, REV. 
SCI. INSTR., Vol 63 No 1, 1992, p 1305. 

</TEXT>

