<H3> <TI>   Micro- and Nanostructure Effects on Mechanical Properties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Micro- and Nanostructure Effects on Mechanical Properties </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
for   Boron Carbide Based Composites 

<F P=102> 43070061K Tokyo ISBB'93 in English Aug 93 p 50--FOR OFFICIAL 
USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 43070061K </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ISBB'93 </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [English abstract of article by Koichi Niihara and Atsushi </F>
Nakahira, ISIR, Osaka University; Tomohiro Yanai, Nagaoka 
Institute of Technology; and Gen Sasaki and Katsuaki Suganuma, 
National Defense Academy] 
  [Text] The effect of micro and nanostructure effects on the 
mechanical properties such as hardness, fracture strength, 
toughness and high-temperature strength were investigated for 
the monolithic B[.sub]4[/]C and B[.sub]4[/]C/SiC, 
B[.sub]4[/]C/TiB[.sub]2[/] and 
B[.sub]4[/]C/SiC/TiB[.sub]2[/] composites. These 
composites were fabricated by hot-pressing the homogeneous 
mixtures of B[.sub]4[/]C, SiC and TiC powders in Ar 
atmosphere at 1900ë to 2200ëC. X-ray diffraction 
analysis indicated that the TiB[.sub]2[/] was formed by 
reacting the TiC with B[.sub]4[/]C during sintering. Scanning 
and high resolution transmission electron microscopic 
observation revealed that the finer SiC and TiB[.sub]2[/] 
grains less than 100nm were mainly dispersed within the 
B[.sub]4[/]C matrix grains, although the larger grains were, 
of course, located at the grain boundaries of B[.sub]4[/]C 
grains. 
  It is well known that the intragranular nanosized grains 
improved remarkably the mechanical properties, in particular, 
the fracture strength even at high temperatures in the composite 
systems such as Al[.sub]2[/]O[.sub]3[/]/SiC, 
Al[.sub]2[/]O[.sub]3[/]/Si[.sub]3[/]N[.sub]4[/], 
MgO/SiC, mullite/SiC, Al[.sub]2[/]O[.sub]3[/]/TiC and 
Si[.sub]3[/]N[.sub]4[/]/SiC. As expected from the results 
reported for these composites, the nanosized TiB[.sub]2[/] 
and SiC strongly improved the mechanical properties of 
B[.sub]4[/]C. The fracture toughness and strength were over 
two times improved as compared with those of monolithic 
B[.sub]4[/]C. And the improved strength and toughness did not 
degradate up to the temperatures of 1200ë to 1300ëC even 
in the air atmosphere. 
  In this presentation, the processes micro- and nanostructure 
mechanical properties relationship will be discussed in detail. 
Special emphasis will be placed on the understanding of the 
nanosized dispersion effects. 

</TEXT>

