<H3> <TI>   New Approximant Phase of Icosahedral Quasicrystal in </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Approximant Phase of Icosahedral Quasicrystal in </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Boron-Carbon   Semiconductor 

<F P=102> 43070061X Tokyo ISBB'93 in English Aug 93 p 105--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 43070061X </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ISBB'93 </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [English abstract of article by Masatoshi Takeda, Akira </F>
Hori, Hideaki Yamashita, Kaoru Kimura, and Hiromitsu Ino, 
Department of Materials Science, University of Tokyo] 
  [Text] In the crystallography, it is assumed that an ideal 
crystal is constructed by the infinite repetition of identical 
structural units in space. Therefore, a five-fold axis of 
symmetry cannot exist in a periodic lattice because it is not 
possible to fill all space with a connected array of pentagons. 
However, in 1984, Scechtman, et al.[.sup]1[/] found a 
material with icosahedral point symmetry in a rapidly solidified 
Al-Mn alloy. This is the first discovery of ``Quasicrystal.'' 
Since the discovery, quasicrystals have been found in many 
kinds, but only metallic alloy systems.[.sup]2[/] It is 
interesting to inquire whether a quasicrystalline structure can 
be stable in a covalent bonding system. Boron-rich solids with 
B[.sub]12[/] icosahedral clusters are great candidates for a 
semiconducting quasicrystal. This is because the icosahedral 
point symmetry is typical for quasicrystalline structure. 
  We analyzed the crystalline structure of the 
_a_-rhombohedral 
boron as a 0/1-2/0 rhombohedral approximant structure of the 
icosahedral quasicrystal, and then constructed the _a_-boron 
type quasicrystal. The cohesive energy of the _a_-, 
_b_-rhombohedral boron and the _a_-boron type quasicrystal 
was 
estimated using a molecular orbital total energy calculation. 
According to the calculation, realization of the _a_-boron type 
quasicrystal is expected. 
  Experimental search for semiconducting quasicrystal has been 
done in the B-C system. The distortion of B[.sub]12[/] is 
smallest in the B-C system. If the B[.sub]12[/] cluster is 
distorted spontaneously, there is no reason why the icosahedral 
symmetry grows. This is why we chose the B-C system. Amorphous 
films of B[.sub]100-x[/]C[.sub]x[/] (x=3,5 and 7) were 
prepared by an electron-beam evaporation technique. Then they 
were examined for the transformation by heat treatment. This is 
because most of the metallic quasicrystals have been found as a 
metastable phase in a nonequilibrium process. We found a new 
phase in the annealing process. The electron and X-ray 
diffraction patterns from the phase are identified to be that of 
the 1/0-1/0-0/1 orthorhombic crystalline approximant of the 
icosahedral quasicrystal. In many cases, the crystalline 
approximants have been found near the composition or temperature 
range in which the quasicrystal is formed. Therefore, it is 
possible to realize the semiconducting quasicrystal in 
boron-rich solids. 
References 
  1. D. Shechtman, I. Blech, D. Gratias, and J.W. Cahn, PHYS. 
REV. LETT.,Vol 53, 1984, p 1951. 
  2. e.g., ``Quasicrystals the State of the Art,'' ed. by D.P. 
DiVicenzo and P.J. Steinhart (World Scientific, Singapore, 1991). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

