<H3> <TI>     Waste Water Recycling Technology Using a Rotary Disk Module </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Waste Water Recycling Technology Using a Rotary Disk Module </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   43070065D Yokohama Proceedings of the IDA and WRPC World 
Conference on Desalination and Water Treatment in English 3-6 </F>



<TEXT>
Nov 93 pp 251-258 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY 
<F P=103> 43070065D </F>
<F P=104>  Yokohama Proceedings of the IDA and WRPC World 
Conference on Desalination and Water Treatment </F>

<F P=105>  English </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by N. Ohkuma, M. Ohnishi, and Y. Okuno of Hitachi </F>
Plant Engineering &amp; Construction Co., Ltd., 537 Kami-hongo, 
Matsudo-shi, Chiba 271, Japan] 
  [Text] 
<H5>  Abstract </H5>
  Rotary disk modules, developed for the separation of highly 
concentrated activated sludge, can be used in place of 
biological settling ponds to efficiently recycle sewage or waste 
water. Applied to sewage treatment, the rotary disk module 
allowed us to consistently obtain recycled water of T-N &lt; 5 
mg/l, BOD &lt; 2 mg/l, SS trace. When the module was applied to 
cafeteria waste water treatment, we were able to obtain recycled 
water of BOD &lt; 2 mg/l, SS trace. Flux through the module was, 
in both cases, able to be maintained at 1.5 
m[.sup]3[/]/m[.sup]2[/]d while filtering liquid of 10 to 
15 g/l MLSS. 
<H5>  Introduction </H5>
  As pollution in closed water regions grows worse and urban 
redevelopment becomes more extensive, it becomes all the more 
urgent to recycle sewage and commercial building waste water. 
Here, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry conducted 
a six-year (1985 through 1990) project, Research and Development 
on General Recycling Systems for Water. In conjunction with 
this, the authors supervised a project, Research and Development 
on Biological Nitrogen Removal Technique, directed at developing 
membrane reactors for sewage recycling. In the field of water 
treatment, membrane reactors have been utilized for grey water 
production devices[.sup]1[/] that combine membrane treatment 
with the activated sludge process. However, while this approach 
does have its advantages, it is limited by the large amount of 
power required to membrane-separate the highly concentrated 
activated sludge. 
  Here, we created a rotary disk module[.sup]2[/] for the 
low-power separation of highly concentrated liquid and, in 
extension, developed a membrane reactor that combines this with 
the biological nitrogen removal process. In this paper, we 
introduce this rotary disk module and the newly developed 
membrane reactor for sewage treatment. In addition, we access 
the performance of this system as applied to the recycling of 
cafeteria waste water and compare its cost to that of 
tubular-type modules. 
<H5>  2. Design of the Rotary Disk Module </H5>
  A conventional membrane module circulates the treatment 
liquid at a high flow rate so as to obtain a rapid flow at the 
membrane surface and a high flux through the surface. However, 
much power is consumed, because the pressure loss within the 
module is correspondingly high (i.e., a higher pressure is 
maintained than what is required for filtration alone). As 
opposed to this, rotating the membrane would, we thought, allow 
us to maintain a high liquid flow rate at the membrane surface 
without having to maintain high pressure. Therefore, relatively 
little power would be required to run the system. 
  The water collection mechanism of a rotary disk module is 
shown in Figure 1. A membrane disk, comprised of two support 
plates covered with a membrane over their surface, is fastened 
to a hollow rotary shaft which acts as a water collection tube. 
Filtering is carried out while the shaft rotates. To modularize 
the system, it is of course necessary to increase the filling 
density of the membrane by attaching many such disks to the 
rotary shaft. However, merely adding on extra disks decreases 
the flux through the surface by approximately one-half in a 
liquid having a high concentration of microorganisms. Here, 
installing baffle plates between the disks restores the flux to 
very nearly what it would be with only one disk.[.sup]3[/] 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-018L-18A>      Figure 1. Water Collection Mechanism of Rotary Disk Module </FIG>


  The engagement-type module (Figure 2) utilizes the disks of 
an adjacent rotary shaft in place of the baffle plates. Here, 
two shafts comprise one module. Not only is membrane filling 
density increased with this arrangement, but turbulent flow at 
the membrane surface is encouraged, thereby increasing the flux. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-018L-18B>      Figure 2. Engagement-Type Rotary Disk Module </FIG>


<H5>  3. Advanced Sewage Recycling System (a part of the Aqua </H5>
Renaissance '90 Project) 
  3-1. Experimental Apparatus 
  The experimental apparatus is comprised of a nitrogen 
removal 
tank (1.25 m[.sup]3[/]), a nitrification tank (1.25 
m[.sup]3[/]), and a rotary disk module (Membrane Area 7.44 
m[.sup]2[/]). Standard treatment capacity is 10 
m[.sup]3[/]/d. Retention time in the bioreaction tank was set 
at 6 hours. The rotary disk module consisted of two shafts, each 
with 12 disks of 500mm in diameter. The membrane was made out of 
a polysulfone. The data presented here was taken when using 
membranes having a cut-off molecular weight of 600,000. 
  The types of raw water were tested: sewage (case 1); water 
from methane-fermentation of sewage (case 2); and water from SS 
separation and from SS methane-fermentation of sewage (case 3). 
Flow paths and operating results are shown in Table 1. Figures 
for water quality shown in the table are average values 
throughout the operating period. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-018L-19A>      FIGURE </FIG>


  3-2. Membrane Reactor Effectiveness 
  The rate of nitrogen removal in the activated sludge process 
increases with an increase in the recirculation ratio. Figure 3 
[not reproduced] presents data showing the effect of 
recirculation ratio in a membrane reactor. In both cases 1 and 
2, we see that, relative to theoretical removal rates for 
conventional processing, higher removal rates were obtained even 
at lower circulation rates. This is because of (a) nitrogen 
removal in the nitrification tank due to a higher concentration 
of microorganisms and (b) removal by the membrane of nitrogen 
components resulting from SS. Here, we note that using membranes 
is very effective. Furthermore, the very high rate of nitrogen 
removal observed in case 2 is due to nearly complete 
nitrification and denitrification resulting from efforts to 
remove nitrogen after nitrification. 
  The microorganisms had been acclimated from some time back, 
so this trial did not last long. Even so, we did achieve stable 
operation from the 15th to 70th day, producing, with retention 
times of 3 to 6 hours, treating water having 5 ml/l or less of 
T-N and 2 mg/l or less of BOD. Furthermore, the amount of excess 
sludge in this period was one-fifth of that resulting from 
conventional process. 
  Operating results for case 2 are shown in Figure 4 [not 
reproduced]. From the 150th day of operation, we began adding 
ammonium chloride to the raw water to increase the nitrogen 
load. Even with this, we were able to maintain stable operation 
throughout the year. In average values throughout the year, 
water quality was 31.3 mg/l total nitrogen and 9.5 mg/l BOD for 
the raw water and 0.93 mg/l nitrogen and less than 2 mg/l BOD 
for the treated water -- the treated water was fully able to be 
recycled. Very little excess sludge was generated during the 
operating period, and nitrogen was removed very efficiently. 
Furthermore, use of the rotary disk module forestalled any 
problems with flow blockage or the like -- the membrane reactor 
operated very smoothly. 
  3-3. Membrane Module Performance 
  Figure 5 [not reproduced] shows the change with time in flux 
upon continuous operation. Nearly the same flux is obtained in 
cases 1 and 2. In case 2, a flux of 1.5 
m[.sup]3[/]/m[.sup]2[/]d was obtained over 180 days of 
operation without chemical cleaning. The pressure at this time 
was low at 0.09 MPa, and the concentration of microorganisms in 
the module was 12 to 15 g/l. The power required to draw water 
through the membrane at this time (cutoff molecular weight = 
600,000, motor efficiency = 85 percent, pump efficiency = 60 
percent) was about 1 kWh/m[.sup]3[/]. By this, we confirmed 
that we could separate highly concentration liquid with 
relatively little power. 
  3-4. Comparison With Conventional Method 
  Table 2 presents a comparison for sewage between the 
conventional process (nitrified liquor recycling activated 
sludge process[.sup]4[/]) and the newly developed membrane 
reactor. Because a high concentration of microorganisms was able 
to be maintained with the membrane reactor, treatment time could 
be reduced by about two-thirds, even at low temperatures, and 
the volume of excess sludge was reduced by about four-fifths. 
The newly developed system consistently produced water of a 
quality -BOD = 2 mg/l max., T-N = 5 ml/l max. -- significantly 
higher than that produced by the conventional system. These and 
other results demonstrate the effectiveness of membrane 
reactors. However, it should be mentioned that the membrane 
reactor is probably not advantageous if the water is to be 
discharged after treatment -- it is only economically feasible 
when the treated water is to be recycled. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-018L-20A>      FIGURE </FIG>


<H5>  4. Cafeteria Waste Water Recycling System </H5>
  4-1. Experimental Apparatus and Methods 
  Figure 6 shows the flow of the experimental apparatus 
(treatment capacity: 3 m[.sup]3[/]/d). The raw water is waste 
water from a cafeteria within the Matsudo Works of Hitachi Plant 
Engineering and Construction. After screening (2.0mm mesh) and 
oil separation (in a tank), the raw water is fed into a 
bioreaction tank (0.8 m[.sup]3[/]) for anaoxic and oxic 
treatment. Afterwards, the water is fed to a rotary disk module 
for solid/liquid separation. By this, treated water is obtained 
for recycling. Concentrated liquid from the module is fed back 
to the anaoxic tank. As treated water is removed from the 
system, an equal quantity of raw water is fed into the 
bioreaction treatment tank. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-018L-21A>      Figure 6. Cafeteria Waste Water Recycling System Flow </FIG>


  The rotary disk module is comprised of two rotary shafts; 
the 
disks on one shaft run between the disks of the other. In this 
experiment, disk diameter is 500mm, and each shaft has six 
disks. The membrane is made of a polysulfone; the cutoff 
molecular weight is 750,000. A constant volume pump was attached 
to the treated water line (offtake) of the rotary disk module. 
The water was pulled through the membrane by the suction force 
of this pump. No chemical cleaning was performed within the 
period of this experiment. 
  4-2. Results of Continuous System Operation 
  The experimental apparatus was run in such a way that BOD-SS 
load was kept at 0.15 kg/kg-d. Figure 7 [not reproduced] shows 
the progression in flux over two months in continuous operation; 
Table 3 shows the results of water quality measurements taken 
over that period (``raw water'' in the table refers to water at 
the inlet of the biological treatment tank). At this time, 
liquid temperature in the biological treatment tank was 25 to 
33ëC, and MLSS was controlled to about 10 g/l. From Table 3, 
we note that high removal rates of over 90 percent were obtained 
for all water quality items and that the treated water was of a 
quality sufficient for recycling. Through this experiment, we 
have confirmed the efficiency of membrane treatment -- flux in 
the rotary disk module averaged 1.5 
m[.sup]3[/]/m[.sup]2[/]d, and simple screening was enough 
to prevent any problems from blockage by foreign objects. 



  Table 3. Water Quality Under Continuous Operation 

Item           Units       Raw water         Treated water     Removal 
                           average (range)   average (range)   rate (%) 


BOD            mg/l        390 (248-575)     1.9 (1.2-3.1)     99.5 

SS             mg/l        109 (34-303)      &lt; 1               &gt;  99.1 

n-hexane       mg/l        32.8              &lt; 2               &gt;  93.3 
extract                    (15.2-89.5) 

pH             -           6.10              7.12              - 
                           (5.54-6.91)       (6.60-7.66) 

T-N            mg/l        11.7              0.88 (0.24-2.1)   92.5 
                           (9.21-14.6) 

COD            mg/l        126.9 (98-228)    7.4 (6.2-8.6)     94.2 


  4.3. Running Cost 
  Table 4 presents a comparison of running costs between a 
rotary disk module and a tubular membrane module. Equipment 
depreciation and maintenance costs are not included. Because the 
rotary disk module, in comparison to the tubular membrane 
module, requires less power for filtration and has a higher 
flux, costs for power can be reduced by about half and costs for 
membrane changes can be reduced by about two-fifths. 



  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Table 4. Running Cost Comparison (treatment capacity: 200 m[.sup]3[/]/d)   | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|                         |Rotary disk              |Tubular type             | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Power costs (%)          |25.3                     |47.9                     | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Membrane replacement cos-|30.4                     |50.2                     | 
|ts (%)                   |                         |                         | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Chemical costs (%)       |0.04                     |1.9                      | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Total                    |55.74                    |100.0                    | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


<H5>  5. Summary </H5>
  Advanced sewage recycling system (a part of the Aqua 
Renaissance '90 Project) 
  (1) The use of a biological nitrogen removal process has 
enabled us to obtain recycled water of T-N &lt; 5 mg/l, BOD &lt; 
2 
mg/l, SS trace. 
  (2) By maintaining the microorganism concentration in the 
bioreaction tank at 10 to 15 g/l, we have succeeded in 
shortening the treatment time to one-third of that required by 
the conventional biological nitrogen removal method. 
  (3) With the rotary disk module, we have achieved stable 
performance and high flux. We also showed that it is possible to 
drive the rotary disk module with less power than required for a 
plate &amp; frame-type module. 
  Cafeteria waste water re-use system 
  In continuous operation, we obtained a stable supply of 
recycled water with a good quality of BOD &lt; 2 mg/l, SS trace. 
Also, we were able to maintain a flux of approximately 1.5 
m[.sup]3[/]/m[.sup]2[/]d without chemical cleaning. 
<H5>  6. Literature Cited </H5>
  1. K. Misaki: Grey water systems using membrane bioreactors, 
Heating Pipe and Air Conditioning 23 (11), pp 94-99 (1985). 
  2. H. Masuda et al.: Study of the UF module with a rotary 
disk membrane, the 1987 International Congress on Membranes and 
Membrane Processes Proceedings, pp 395-396 (1987). 
  3. N. Ohkuma et al.: Application of a rotary disk membrane 
type UF module to the activated sludge process, ibid., pp 
408-409 (1987). 
  4. K. Mori: Advanced treatment at Kasumigaura, Journal of 
Japan Sewage Works Association (318), pp 18-21 (1990). 

